trace.verification_evidence:
{
  "red_failure_evidence": "Before the work the verify aborted under set -e at the timeout assertion, exit 1 with no output: control-loop.sh had no timeout at all, so a hung claude invocation would block forever and the stop file - only read at the top of an iteration - would never be re-read, leaving the human nothing but killing the pane. Both scripts also resolved the stop file relative to their own invoker cwd, so the bootstrap guard and the loop checked different files, and bootstrap would create a second cockpit and a second dispatch loop against the same backlog on every run.",
  "green_evidence": "RUNNER_HARDENED / rc=0, re-run independently by the orchestrator, with three failing iterations all running and a pre-existing stop file yielding zero. I also ran a case the verify does not cover, to prove the timeout is not a disguised exit path: --timeout 1 against a command sleeping 5s produced three 'iteration timed out after 1s; reported as a failed iteration, continuing' lines and three recorded iterations, so the loop survives a hang exactly as it survives an error.",
  "orchestrator_review": "The timeout is handled as rc 124 alongside every other non-zero exit and adds no new exit branch, which was the trap here - a timeout that terminates the loop would have quietly undone D19, the one property this feature proved structurally rather than by instruction. Noted with concern: the worker used git stash to reconstruct the pre-edit state for the red capture, in a repo whose stash stack is shared across worktrees and concurrent sessions. It restored cleanly and the stack is empty now, but that was a risk it did not need to take."
}
